  issn          = {0164-1212},
  abstract      = {Model-based specification languages, in particular Z, have
                  been widely used to provide a precise and unambiguous
                  statement of the proposed system as perceived by the
                  developer. However, for many complex specifications,
                  developers cannot themselves be sure about the ``intended
                  behaviour'' of the specification constructed. This paper
                  reports on an approach and toolset that enables a developer
                  to construct a Z specification using the wiZe editor,
                  demonstrate its properties by transforming it into an
                  executable form using the ZAL animation system, and explore
                  its adequacy by animating a variety of scenarios. The
                  application of the approach and toolset is demonstrated on
                  a specification of a telephone network to illustrate that
                  specification validation could be carried our incrementally
                  during development through investigative scenarios to
                  assess the adequacy of the specification. II is claimed
                  that this interaction, when used in peer review or by the
